L,NULL,NULL),(96,'Annihilator_Method',6,23,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(97,'CauchyANDEuler',8,23,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(98,'Variation_of_Parameters',9,23,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(99,'Power_Series_Solutions',7,23,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(100,'Laplace_Transforms',10,23,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(101,'Power_Rule',3,24,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(102,'Product_Rule',4,24,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(103,'Quotient_Rule',5,24,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(104,'Chain_Rule',6,24,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(105,'Introduction',1,24,'Definition','Consequence of Differentiability',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Given some arbitrary function, $f(x)$, consider the following setup:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<img src=\"/content/Differential_Calculus/The_Derivative/Introduction/Secant.png\">\n</div>\nwhere the line that passes through the two points is known as the $\\textit{secant}$ line. Formally we would write down the average rate of change, the slope of the secant line, as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{f(x_1) - f(x_0)}{x_1 - x_0}\n	}$\n</div>\nIdeally say that we want to find the $\\textit{instantaneous}$ rate of change at $x = x_0$, how would this be attained given the current setup? With an understanding of limits, we can develop a systematic way of approaching a point infinitesimally close. To do this just let $x_1 \\rightarrow x_0$, giving:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{df}{dx} \\Big|_{x = x_0} = f\'(x_0) = \\lim_{x_1 \\rightarrow x_0} \\frac{f(x_1) - f(x_0)}{x_1 - x_0}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere the above is known as the derivative of $f(x)$ evaluated at $x = x_0$. Formally we state a function is $\\textit{differentiable}$ at $x = x_0$ iff $f\'(x_0)$ exists. The above can also be rewritten if the following substitutions are used:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		h &= x_1 - x_0 \\\\\n		x_1 \\rightarrow x_0 &\\implies h \\rightarrow 0\n	}$\n</div>\ngiving:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{df}{dx} \\Big|_{x = x_0} = f\'(x_0) = \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{f(x_0 + h) - f(x_0)}{h}\n	}$\n</div>\nEither definition is valid and can be generalized to determining the derivative function as whole and not just at a point. Formally:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{df}{dx} = f\'(x) = \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{f(x + h) - f(x)}{h}\n	}$\n</div>\nthe above is known as the derivative function and determines the instantaneous rate of change of the original function at any $x$. ','I say consequence, but do not mean it in a bad way. Actually if a function is differentiable at a point, then it is also continuous at that point. Extending this we say that if a function is differentiable on some interval, then it is also continuous on that interval.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(106,'Implicit_Differentiation',7,24,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(107,'Logarithmic_Differentiation',8,24,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(108,'Introduction',1,25,'Definition','Graphical Approach','Numerical Approach','Analytical Approach','Indeterminate Forms',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'The $\\textit{limit}$ of a function, $f(x)$, as $x \\rightarrow a$ is written as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} f(x) = L\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere $L$ is some real number. A limit in essense is the process of determining what value $f(x)$ approaches as we look near $a$. Note that during this process we have to consider that the image at hand is a one dimensional line for $x$ and so there are two directions in which we can approach $a$, left and right. As a consequence we say that a limit will only exist if it is the same value being approached from both sides.','One of the standard approaches to evaluating limits is a graphical one. Take for example the following graph of a piecewise function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<img src=\"/content/Differential_Calculus/Limits/Introduction/Example_Function.gif\">\n</div>\nLets say that we want to determine what the limit of the function is as $x \\rightarrow 1$. To do this look at the graph and observe that as $x$ approaches $1$ from both the left side and right side, the function approaches $1$. So formally:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 1} f(x) = 1\n	}$\n</div>\nNotice that even though the limit says the function approaches $1$, in reality $f(1) = 2$. So in general the function evaluated at a point and the limit at the point do not have to equate. As another example consider the scenario where $x \\rightarrow 2$, what is the limit of the function now? As we approach from the left side we get a value of $2$, but from the right side we get $3$. So formally:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 2} f(x) = \\text{DNE}\n	}$\n</div>\nsince the two sides do not approach the same value. ','Another standard method to evaluate limits is to use a numerical approach. Essentially the goal is to check the pattern of the function near the point of interest by directly calculating the function. For example consider the function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = \\frac{x^2 - 1}{x + 1}\n	}$\n</div>\nYou should be able to note that the function has a vertical asymptote at $x = -1$, but what is the limit as $x \\rightarrow -1$? To do this numerically, just create a table of values and observe the patten from both sides:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<table>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>$\\textbf{x}$</td>\n		    <td>$\\textbf{f(x)}$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>$-1.100$</td>\n		    <td>$-2.100$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>$-1.010$</td>\n		    <td>$-2.010$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>$-1.001$</td>\n		    <td>$-2.001$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>$-0.999$</td>\n		    <td>$-1.999$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>$-0.990$</td>\n		    <td>$-1.990$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>$-0.900$</td>\n		    <td>$-1.900$</td>\n		</tr>\n	</table>\n</div>\nHopefully you notice from the table that as $x \\rightarrow -1$, the function approaches $-2$. So formally:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow -1} f(x) = -2\n	}$\n</div>','Besides the graphical approach which involves just looking at a graph to determine the limit and the numerical approach which is nothing more than a brute force method to determine the limit, there also exists the analytical approach to evaluating a limit. This approach involves nothing more than using some mathematical intuition to evaluate the limit. For example consider the same function as before:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = \\frac{x^2 - 1}{x + 1}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich officially has a vertical asymptote at $x = -1$. To evaluate the limit directly:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow -1} f(x) &= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow -1} \\frac{x^2 - 1}{x + 1} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow -1} \\frac{(x - 1)(x + 1)}{x + 1} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow -1} (x - 1) \\\\\n		&= -2\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich happens to work since the vertical asymptote is a removable singularity. Yet, this brings up an interesting point when evaluating the second to last line. Why is it that I am allowed to just plug in the value of $x = -1$ to evaluate the limit? It so happens that in general if we have a known continuous function, $g(x)$, we are allowed to say that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} g(x) = g(a)\n	}$\n</div>\nBesides the removable singularity, another common trick involves using the conjugate. For example consider the function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		k(x) = \\frac{x - 1}{\\sqrt{x} - 1}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere the limit as $x \\rightarrow 1$ is:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 1} k(x) &= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow 1} \\frac{x - 1}{\\sqrt{x} - 1} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow 1} \\frac{x - 1}{\\sqrt{x} - 1} \\cdot \\frac{\\sqrt{x} + 1}{\\sqrt{x} + 1} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow 1} \\frac{(x - 1)(\\sqrt{x} + 1)}{x - 1} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow 1} (\\sqrt{x} + 1) \\\\\n		&= 2\n	}$\n</div>','When dealing with limits, something that you may typically run across are $\\textit{indeterminate forms}$, which are expressions that do not hold any numerical expression since they approach different values under certain conditions. In the context of literature, some common examples of indetermine forms include, but are not limited to:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{0}{0}, \\frac{\\infty}{\\infty}, 0 \\times \\infty, \\infty - \\infty, 0^0, 1^\\infty, \\hspace{.1cm} \\text{and} \\hspace{.1cm} \\infty^0\n	}$\n</div>\nIf a limit does take on one of these values, it does not guarantee that the limit does not exist, but rather it implies that more work will have to be performed to figure out the limit. ',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(109,'OneANDSided_Limits',2,25,'Definition','Existence of a Limit','Vertical Asymptotes',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'In the previous section I discussed the idea of a limit and mentioned that it only exists if the function approaches the same value from the left and right sides. Now to be more formal, I provide for you a representation of the left-limit as $x \\rightarrow a$:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a^-} f(x) = L_1\n	}$\n</div>\nand right-limit:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a^+} f(x) = L_2\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere $L_1$ and $L_2$ are some real numbers that do not necessarily have to be the same. To determine the above limits, we only have to observe one side of the function now rather than making sure both sides equate.','With the above notation for one-sided limits, we can now state that a limit of a function, $f(x)$, as $x \\rightarrow a$ will exist iff:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a^-} f(x) = \\lim_{x \\rightarrow a^+} f(x)\n	}$\n</div>','If any one of the following occurs as $x \\rightarrow a$ for a function $f(x)$:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a^-} f(x) &= -\\infty \\\\\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a^-} f(x) &= \\infty \\\\\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a^+} f(x) &= -\\infty \\\\\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a^+} f(x) &= \\infty\n	}$\n</div>\nthen the funciton has a $\\textit{vertical asymptote}$ at $x = a$.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(110,'Limit_Properties',3,25,'Introduction','Linearity','Multiplication','Division','Constant','Power Function','Power',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Having seen limits and how they are determined, you should now wonder if there exist properties that could simplify calculations for us. Fortunately, there are and below you will a list of the properties exhibited by all limits.','Limits are linear operators, thus:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} (\\alpha f(x) + \\beta g(x)) &= \\alpha \\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} f(x) + \\beta \\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} g(x) \\\\\n		\\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} &\\alpha, \\beta \\in \\mathbb{R}\n	}$\n</div>\niff the limit of each function exists.','Limits involving multiplication can be split:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} (f(x) \\cdot g(x)) = \\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} f(x) \\cdot \\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} g(x)\n	}$\n</div>\niff the limit of each function exists.','Limits involving division can be split\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} \\frac{f(x)}{g(x)} &= \\Big[ \\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} f(x) \\Big] \\Big[ \\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} g(x) \\Big]^{-1} \\\\\n		\\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} g(x) &\\neq 0 \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{and} \\hspace{.3cm} \\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} g(x) \\neq 0\n	}$\n</div>\niff the limit of each function exists.','All limits involving just a constant do nothing:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} c = c \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} c \\in \\mathbb{R}\n	}$\n</div>','All limits involving a power function are evaluated as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} x^n = a^n \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} n \\in \\mathbb{R}\n	}$\n</div>','All limits involving a function raised to a power are evaluated as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} (f(x))^n = \\Big[ \\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} f(x) \\Big]^n \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} n \\in \\mathbb{R}\n	}$\n</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL),(111,'Limits_with_Infinity',4,25,'Limits at Infinity','Horizontal Asymptotes',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'To analyze a function\'s end behavior, we look at the two limits all the way on the left and right:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow -\\infty} f(x) &= L_1 \\\\\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} f(x) &= L_2\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere $L_1$ and $L_2$ are some real numbers, generally not the same.','Determining the $\\textit{horizontal asymptotes}$ for a given rational function is exactly the same as computing the limit at infinity. In general given the rational function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		g(x) = \\frac{a_0 + a_1x + a_2x^2 + \\dots + a_nx^n}{b_0 + b_1x + b_2x^2 + \\dots + b_mx^m}\n	}$\n</div>\nthere exist a couple of different scenarios:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<table>\n	<tr>\n		<td>$\\textbf{Situation}$</td>\n		<td>$\\eqalign{\\lim_{x \\rightarrow -\\infty} g(x)}$</td>\n		    <td>$\\eqalign{\\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} g(x)}$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$n > m$: One odd, the other even</td>\n		    <td>$-\\infty$</td>\n		    <td>$\\infty$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$n > m$: Both odd, or even</td>\n		    <td>$\\infty$</td>\n		    <td>$\\infty$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$n = m$</td>\n		    <td>$\\frac{a_n}{b_m}$</td>\n		    <td>$\\frac{a_n}{b_m}$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$n < m$</td>\n		    <td>$0$</td>\n		    <td>$0$</td>\n		</tr>\n	</table>\n</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(112,'Continuity',5,25,'Introduction','Continuity at a Point','Continuity on an Interval','Continuous Functions','Limit of Composition of Functions','Squeeze Theorem','Bolzano\'s Theorem','Proof of Bolzano\'s Theorem_hidden','Intermediate Value Theorem','Proof of Intermediate Value Theorem_hidden','Now we finally introduce continuity and unravel the \"nice\" behavior that is seen across all continuous functions.','A function, $f(x)$, is said to be $\\textit{continuous at a point}$, $x = a$, if:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} &f(x) \\hspace{.2cm} \\text{exists}, \\hspace{.1cm} f(a) \\hspace{.2cm} \\text{is defined,} \\\\\n		&\\text{and} \\hspace{.2cm} f(a) = \\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} f(x)\n	}$\n</div>','A function, $f(x)$, is said to be $\\textit{continuous}$ on an interval, $S \\subseteq \\mathbb{R}$, if it is continuous at every point in $S$.','Given two continuous functions, $f(x)$ and $g(x)$, the following are also continuous:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\text{Scalar Multiple:}& \\hspace{.3cm} \\alpha f(x) \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} \\alpha \\in \\mathbb{R} \\\\\n		\\text{Sum:}& \\hspace{.3cm} f(x) + g(x) \\\\\n		\\text{Product:}& \\hspace{.3cm} f(x)g(x) \\\\\n		\\text{Quotient:}& \\hspace{.3cm} \\frac{f(x)}{g(x)} \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} g(x) \\neq 0\n	}$\n</div>','Given that a function, $f(x)$, is continuous at $x = L$ where:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} g(x) = L\n	}$\n</div>\nthen:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} f(g(x)) = f\\Big( \\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} g(x) \\Big)\n	}$\n</div>','Limits are known to preserve inequalities, so given two functions s.t.:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) \\leq g(x)\n	}$\n</div>\nthen:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} f(x) \\leq \\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} g(x)\n	}$\n</div>\nUsing this information consider a scenario where we have three functions s.t.:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		h(x) \\leq f(x) \\leq g(x)\n	}$\n</div>\nand it is known that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} h(x) = \\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} g(x) = L\n	}$\n</div>\nthen:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} f(x) = L\n	}$\n</div>','Given a continuous function on the closed interval $[a,b]$ where $f(a)$ and $f(b)$ have opposite signs, then:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\exists \\hspace{.2cm} c \\in (a,b) \\hspace{.5cm} \\text{s.t.} f(c) = 0\n	}$\n</div>\nIn other words Bolzano\'s Theorem guarantees that a continuous function attains a zero on the interval so long as the function evaluation at the endpoints produces opposite signs.','While the theorem is very straight forward, the proof requires a bit more insight. First lets assume that we have a continuous function on the compact interval $[a,b]$ s.t. $f(a) < 0$ and $f(b) > 0$. Now define a new point:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		a_1 = \\frac{a + b}{2}\n	}$\n</div>\nto be the average of the two endpoints where three cases can occur:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(a_1) = 0 \\implies &\\text{the theorem is proved} \\\\\n		f(a_1) > 0 \\implies &\\text{define a new interval} \\\\\n		& I_1 = (a, a_1) \\\\\n		f(a_1) < 0 \\implies &\\text{define a new interval} \\\\\n		& I_1 = (a_1, b) \\\\\n	}$\n</div>\nIgnoring the trivial case we now have the original interval $I_0 = (a,b)$ and $I_1 \\subset I_0$ where the length of the new interval is $|I_1| = \\frac{|I_0|}{2}$. Repeating the above procedure will define a succession of open intervals $I_n = (a_n, b_n)$ s.t. $I_{n + 1} \\subset I_n$, $|I_n| = 2^{-n} |I_0|$, and $f(a_n) < 0 < f(b_n)$. The succession $c_n = a_n$ and $c_{n + 1} = b_n$ is Cauchy by construction since:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\forall m > n \\hspace{.5cm} |c_m - c_n| < 2^{-\\frac{n}{2}} |I_0|\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich implies that $c_n$ is convergent, $c_n \\rightarrow c \\in (a,b)$. Since $a_n$ and $b_n$ are sub-successions they also tend to the same limit. So by construction:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(a_n) &< 0 \\\\\n		\\lim_{n \\rightarrow \\infty} f(a_n) &< 0 \\\\\n		f\\Big( \\lim_{n \\rightarrow \\infty} a_n \\Big) &\\leq 0 \\\\\n		f(c) &\\leq 0\n	}$\n</div>\nand:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(b_n) &> 0 \\\\\n		\\lim_{n \\rightarrow \\infty} f(b_n) &> 0 \\\\\n		f\\Big( \\lim_{n \\rightarrow \\infty} b_n \\Big) &\\geq 0 \\\\\n		f(c) &\\geq 0\n	}$\n</div>\nWith both of the restrictions in mind we must have it s.t. $f(c) = 0$. To finish up we state that $c \\in (a,b)$ because $f(a) < 0$ and $f(b) > 0$. Of course it is the same process for proving the case where $f(a) > 0$ and $f(b) < 0$ if you consider the scenario for $-f(x)$.','Given a continuous function on the closed interval $[a,b]$, according to the $\\textit{Intermediate Value Theorem}$ the function is guaranteed to attain the range:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\mathcal{R}(f) = \\Big[ \\min\\{f(a),f(b)\\}, \\max\\{f(a),f(b)\\} \\Big]\n	}$\n</div>\nIn other words:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\forall \\alpha \\in \\mathcal{R}(f) \\hspace{.1cm} \\exists \\hspace{.1cm} c \\in [a,b] \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{s.t.} \\hspace{.3cm} f(c) = \\alpha\n	}$\n</div>','Begin by assuming we have a continuous function, $f(x)$, on the compact interval $[a,b]$ and want to know whether a $c \\in (a,b)$ exists s.t. $f(c) = L$ where $L$ is a real number between $f(a)$ and $f(b)$. Define a new function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		g(x) = f(x) - L\n	}$\n</div>\nand now we know that $g(a)$ and $g(b)$ will have opposite signs. Therefore, by Bolzano\'s Theorem there will exist a $c \\in (a,b)$ s.t. $g(c) = 0$ which implies:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(c) = L\n	}$\n</div>\nSince $L$ is any arbitrary number in between $f(a)$ and $f(b)$, we know that the function must attain every value in between including the boundaries.'),(113,'Bisection_Method',6,25,'Introduction','Algorithm','Convergence_hidden',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Having Bolzano\'s Theorem in your arsenal actually provides the foundation necessary for a fundamental root-finding algorithm. Known as the $\\textit{Bisection Method}$, the process provides a systematic approach to determine the root of a function given that the function evaluation at the endpoints is of opposite signs.','Given a continuous function on the closed interval $[a,b]$ where $f(a)$ and $f(b)$ have opposite signs, then $\\exists c \\in (a,b)$ s.t. $f(c) = 0$ according to Bolzano\'s Theorem. To determine the value of $c$ follow the steps:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		1. &\\text{Calculate the midpoint of the interval:} \\hspace{.2cm} c = \\frac{a + b}{2} \\\\\n		2. &\\text{Evaluate} \\hspace{.2cm} f(c) \\\\\n		3. &\\text{If the evaluation is close enough to zero} \\\\\n		&\\text{return the value of} \\hspace{.2cm} c \\\\\n		4. &\\text{If the evaluation is not close enough then begin by} \\\\\n		&\\text{checking the sign of} \\hspace{.2cm} f(c). \\hspace{.2cm} \\text{If} \\hspace{.2cm} f(a) \\hspace{.2cm} \\text{and} \\hspace{.2cm} f(c) \\\\\n		&\\text{have the same sign then:} \\hspace{.2cm} b = c, \\hspace{.2cm} \\text{otherwise} \\hspace{.2cm} a = c \\\\\n		&\\text{and you repeat the steps starting from number one.}\n	}$\n</div>\nAt the end of the day the Bisection Method is nothing more than a process of determining the root by guessing the middle value of subintervals.','While the algorithm is very straight forward, the proof requires a bit more insight. First assume that we have a continuous function on the compact interval $[a,b]$ s.t. $f(a) < 0$ and $f(b) > 0$. Now define the middle point:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		a_1 = \\frac{a + b}{2}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere the evaluation can result in three cases:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(a_1) = 0 \\implies &\\text{the value is found} \\\\\n		f(a_1) > 0 \\implies &\\text{define a new interval} \\\\\n		& I_1 = (a, a_1) \\\\\n		f(a_1) < 0 \\implies &\\text{define a new interval} \\\\\n		& I_1 = (a_1, b) \\\\\n	}$\n</div>\nIgnoring the trivial case we now have the original interval $I_0 = (a,b)$ and $I_1 \\subset I_0$ where the length of the new interval is $|I_1| = \\frac{|I_0|}{2}$. Repeating the above procedure will define a succession of open intervals $I_n = (a_n, b_n)$ s.t. $I_{n + 1} \\subset I_n$, and $|I_n| = 2^{-n} |I_0|$. Using the restriction:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		|I_n| &= 2^{-n} |I_0| \\\\\n		\\lim_{n \\rightarrow \\infty} |I_n| &= \\lim_{n \\rightarrow \\infty} 2^{-n} |I_0| \\\\\n		\\lim_{n \\rightarrow \\infty} |I_n| &= 0\n	}$\n</div>\nstates that the interval eventually becomes just a single point, specifically the point we are looking for. By Bolzano\'s Theorem we also know that this point will always exist.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(114,'Common_Derivatives_and_Properties',2,24,'Derivative Properties','Common Derivatives',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'$\n	\\DeclareMathOperator{\\sech}{sech}\n	\\DeclareMathOperator{\\csch}{csch}\n	\\DeclareMathOperator{\\arcsec}{arcsec}\n	\\DeclareMathOperator{\\arccot}{arccot}\n	\\DeclareMathOperator{\\arccsc}{arccsc}\n	\\DeclareMathOperator{\\arccosh}{arccosh}\n	\\DeclareMathOperator{\\arcsinh}{arcsinh}\n	\\DeclareMathOperator{\\arctanh}{arctanh}\n	\\DeclareMathOperator{\\arcsech}{arcsech}\n	\\DeclareMathOperator{\\arccsch}{arccsch}\n	\\DeclareMathOperator{\\arccoth}{arccoth}\n$\n\nSince the derivative is defined through a limit, it is also a linear operator satisfying:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{dx} (\\alpha f(x) + \\beta g(x)) = \\alpha\\frac{d}{dx} f(x) + \\beta\\frac{d}{dx} g(x)\n	}$\n</div>\nfor some constants $\\alpha$ and $\\beta$ which can be seen by direct evaluation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&\\frac{d}{dx} (\\alpha f(x) + \\beta g(x)) \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{1}{h} \\Bigg[ (\\alpha f(x + h) + \\beta g(x + h)) - (\\alpha f(x) + \\beta g(x)) \\Bigg] \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{1}{h} \\Bigg[ \\alpha(f(x + h) - f(x)) + \\beta(g(x + h) - g(x)) \\Bigg] \\\\\n		&= \\alpha \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{f(x + h) - f(x)}{h} + \\beta \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{g(x + h) - g(x)}{h} \\\\\n		&= \\alpha\\frac{d}{dx} f(x) + \\beta\\frac{d}{dx} g(x)\n	}$\n</div>','In the following sections I will introduce you to rules that apply to handling all common cases of differentiation, but before doing that you must first know the fundamental derivatives. I will not go into proving how these are attained here, but perhaps in later examples you will see how the derivative is determined in some specific cases. So for now just accept the following:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<table>\n	<tr>\n		<td>$\\textbf{f(x)}$</td>\n		    <td>$\\frac{d}{dx} \\textbf{f(x)}$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$c$ where $c \\in \\mathbb{R}$</td>\n		    <td>$0$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$x^n$ where $n \\in \\mathbb{R} \\setminus \\{0\\}$</td>\n		    <td>$nx^{n - 1}$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$e^x$</td>\n		    <td>$e^x$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$a^x$ where $a \\in \\mathbb{R}_{> 0}$</td>\n		    <td>$\\ln(a)a^x$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$\\ln(x)$</td>\n		    <td>$\\frac{1}{x}$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$\\log_{a}(x)$ where $a \\in \\mathbb{R}_{> 0}$</td>\n		    <td>$\\frac{1}{\\ln(a)x}$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$\\sin(x)$</td>\n		    <td>$\\cos(x)$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$\\cos(x)$</td>\n		    <td>$-\\sin(x)$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$\\tan(x)$</td>\n		    <td>$\\sec^2(x)$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$\\csc(x)$</td>\n		    <td>$-\\csc(x)\\cot(x)$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$\\sec(x)$</td>\n		    <td>$\\sec(x)\\tan(x)$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$\\cot(x)$</td>\n		    <td>$-\\csc^2(x)$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$\\arcsin(x)$</td>\n		    <td>$\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{1 - x^2}}$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$\\arccos(x)$</td>\n		    <td>$-\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{1 - x^2}}$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$\\arctan(x)$</td>\n		    <td>$\\frac{1}{1 + x^2}$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$\\arccsc(x)$</td>\n		    <td>$-\\frac{1}{|x|\\sqrt{x^2 - 1}}$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$\\arcsec(x)$</td>\n		    <td>$\\frac{1}{|x|\\sqrt{x^2 - 1}}$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$\\arccot(x)$</td>\n		    <td>$-\\frac{1}{1 + x^2}$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$\\sinh(x)$</td>\n		    <td>$\\cosh(x)$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$\\cosh(x)$</td>\n		    <td>$\\sinh(x)$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$\\tanh(x)$</td>\n		    <td>$\\sech^2(x)$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$\\csch(x)$</td>\n		    <td>$-\\csch(x)\\coth(x)$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$\\sech(x)$</td>\n		    <td>$-\\sech(x)\\tanh(x)$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$\\coth(x)$</td>\n		    <td>$-\\csch^2(x)$</td>\n		</tr>\n	</table>\n</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(115,'Implications_of_the_First_Derivative',3,26,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(116,'Implications_of_the_Second_Derivative',4,26,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(117,'Absolute_Extremas',6,26,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(118,'Optimization',7,26,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(119,'Linear_Approximation',8,26,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(120,'LAPOSTROPHEHospitalAPOSTROPHEs_Rule',9,26,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(121,'The_Mean_Value_Theorem',1,26,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(122,'NewtonAPOSTROPHEs_Method',10,26,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(123,'Related_Rates',5,26,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(124,'Secant_Method',11,26,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(125,'HalleyAPOSTROPHEs_Method',12,26,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(126,'Implications_of_the_nth_Derivative',5,26,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(127,'Formal_Definitions',7,25,'Introduction','Definition of a Limit','Left Limit','Right Limit','Limit Leading to Positive Infinity','Limit Leading to Negative Infinity','Limit at Positive Infinity','Limit at Negative Infinity','Continuity at a Point',NULL,'All previous sections talked about limits in terms of how they are evaluated and the associated properties, but not once mentioned the basic notion of where limits actually come from and any formal definitions. To fix this, below I present to you the formal definitions of everything covered in the previous sections with proof-based examples to follow.','The formal definition states that the limit:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} f(x) = L\n	}$\n</div>\nexists if $\\forall \\epsilon > 0, \\exists \\delta > 0$ s.t.:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		|f(x) - L| < \\epsilon \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{whenever} \\hspace{.3cm} |x - a| < \\delta\n	}$\n</div>\nIn all essense this is just a rigorous way of stating that a limit at a point will exist if for every range close to the limit, a value can be determined that also instills a range on the independent variable. So no matter how close you get to the limit, there will always exist a restriction on the domain s.t. the closer you get to the limit, the closer you get to $x = a$. Visually this looks like:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<img src=\"/content/Differential_Calculus/Limits/Formal_Definitions/Limit_Definition.png\">\n</div>','The left-hand limit:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a^-} f(x) = L_1\n	}$\n</div>\nexists if $\\forall \\epsilon > 0, \\exists \\delta > 0$ s.t.:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		|f(x) - L_1| < \\epsilon \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{whenever} \\hspace{.3cm} -\\delta < x - a < 0\n	}$\n</div>\nThis is exactly the same as the definition of the limit, except we now only care about the behavior on the left-hand side as seen on the restriction of $x$.','The right-hand limit:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a^+} f(x) = L_2\n	}$\n</div>\nexists if $\\forall \\epsilon > 0, \\exists \\delta > 0$ s.t.:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		|f(x) - L_2| < \\epsilon \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{whenever} \\hspace{.3cm} 0 < x - a < \\delta\n	}$\n</div>\nThis is exactly the same as the definition of the limit, except we now only care about the behavior on the right-hand side as seen on the restriction of $x$.','We say that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} f(x) = \\infty\n	}$\n</div>\nif $\\forall \\Omega > 0, \\exists \\delta > 0$ s.t.:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) > \\Omega \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{whenever} \\hspace{.3cm} |x - a| < \\delta \n	}$\n</div>\nIn essense this states that no matter how large a value you pick, $f(x)$ will always attain a larger value on some domain close to the value $x = a$.','We say that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} f(x) = -\\infty\n	}$\n</div>\nif $\\forall \\Gamma < 0, \\exists \\delta > 0$ s.t.:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) < \\Gamma \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{whenever} \\hspace{.3cm} |x - a| < \\delta \n	}$\n</div>\nIn essense this states that no matter how small a value you pick, $f(x)$ will always attain a smaller value on some domain close to the value $x = a$.','We say that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} f(x) = \\kappa_1\n	}$\n</div>\nif $\\forall \\epsilon > 0, \\exists \\Omega > 0$ s.t.:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		|f(x) - \\kappa_1| < \\epsilon \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{whenever} \\hspace{.3cm} x > \\Omega \n	}$\n</div>\nIn essense this states that $f(x)$ will attain values close to $\\kappa_1$ at large values of $x$, and as $x$ gets larger $f(x)$ will tend towards exactly $\\kappa_1$.','We say that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow -\\infty} f(x) = \\kappa_2\n	}$\n</div>\nif $\\forall \\epsilon > 0, \\exists \\Gamma < 0$ s.t.:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		|f(x) - \\kappa_2| < \\epsilon \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{whenever} \\hspace{.3cm} x < \\Gamma \n	}$\n</div>\nIn essense this states that $f(x)$ will attain values close to $\\kappa_2$ at small values of $x$, and as $x$ gets smaller $f(x)$ will tend towards exactly $\\kappa_2$.','We say that a function is continuous at a point $x = a$ if $\\forall \\epsilon > 0, \\exists \\delta > 0$ s.t.:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		|f(x) - f(a)| < \\epsilon \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{whenever} \\hspace{.3cm} |x - a| < \\delta \n	}$\n</div>\nIn essense this statement is exactly the same as definition of the limit, except we replace the arbitrary real number, $L$, with the function at that point, $f(a)$.',NULL);
