INSERT INTO `subject` VALUES (5,'Ordinary_Differential_Equations',5,NULL,NULL),(6,'Differential_Calculus',1,'Differential calculus is usually the first calculus course that any undergraduate will take where the subject typically deals with studying the origin, methods to compute, and applications of the derivative as a mathematical tool. To motivate the need for the derivative consider the setup for the average slope of a function, $f(x)$, at any point, having picked out some initial point $x_0$. The slope at $x$ in reference to the starting point is defined as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		g(x) = \\frac{f(x) - f(x_0)}{x - x_0}\n	}$\n</div>\nNow while average is fine and all, we commonly want to find the most accurate slope that we can, the $\\textit{instantaneous}$ rate of change. This can be achieved by moving the starting point or the current point closer to the other. So formally the instantaneous rate of change, or $\\textit{derivative}$, is defined as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{dx} f(x) = \\lim_{x \\rightarrow x_0} \\frac{f(x) - f(x_0)}{x - x_0}\n	}$\n</div>\nAs a specific example, in classical mechanics the velocity, $v(t)$, of an object is defined as the derivative of the displacement, $x(t)$:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		v(t) = \\frac{d}{dt} x(t)\n	}$\n</div>\nBeyond just physics, the derivative is also commonly used to solve optimization problems, help determine the behavior of a function, and even extends to the study of complex variables.','Here you will find all the notation used throughout the study of differential calculus and its corresponding meaning:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<table>\n	<tr>\n		<td>$y\'$ or $y\'(x)$</td>\n		    <td>Lagrange\'s Notation for the First Derivative</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$y\'\'$ or $y\'\'(x)$</td>\n		    <td>Lagrange\'s Notation for the Second Derivative</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$y\'\'\'$ or $y\'\'\'(x)$</td>\n		    <td>Lagrange\'s Notation for the Third Derivative</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$y^{(n)}$ or $y^{(n)}(x)$</td>\n		    <td>The $n$th Derivative</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$\\frac{d^ny}{dx^n}$</td>\n		    <td>Leibniz\'s Notation for the $n$th Derivative</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$\\frac{d^ny}{dx^n} \\Big|_{x = x_0}$</td>\n		    <td>Leibniz\'s Notation for the $n$th Derivative Evaluted at $x = x_0$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$C^{n}$</td>\n		    <td>Set of Functions that have $n$ Continuous Derivatives</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$C^{n}(I)$</td>\n		    <td>Set of Functions that have $n$ Continuous Derivatives on the Domain $I$</td>\n		</tr>\n	</table>\n</div>');
